Ideas: Software review for reproducible research (in econometrics)
##################################################################

Title ideas:
  - Reproducible Econometric Research
  - Strategies and Tools for Reproducible Research
  - Forensic Econometrics
  
Outline ideas:
  o Objectives:
      - Software review
      - Replication excercises
      ------------------------
      - Tutorial on how to make reproducibility more convenient
      - Guidelines for better journal requirements for reproducibility
      - Discussion of incentive problems relating to reproducibility
  o Starting point:
    Econometric research papers often contain (1) theory/new
    methods, (2) simulations, (3) empirical analysis.
    There is some consensus that proofs/justifications should
    be included in within a publication for (1). But for (2)
    and (3), it is often difficult (or impossible) to 
    reproduce the published results. In particular, for
    readers but also for the authors themselves.  Proofs are
    not that different, references to other results in the
    literature often have the feel of missing functions/packages ...
  o Why should we want to improve the situation?
      - Authors put a lot of work into this anyway. Some
        tools and strategies can help them to reproduce
	or modify their own results...often with only small
	efforts. Furthermore, the availability of more insights
	into the details of an analysis facilitate communcation
	of ideas and results to the reader.
      - Readers should expect authors (and publishers) to
        assure reproducibility as this is the basis for research
	=> Claerbout's principle.  Yes, this is really the most
        essential point that communicating a complete version of
	the idea requires the details to be filled in.  Analogies
	with bench experiments in science really illustrates how
	much better the tools are for documenting what was done
	in computational settings.
  o Tools and strategies:
      - Make data available. Often already enforced, e.g., in JAE.
	preferably with some details on where it came from and what
	the protocol was for getting to the final version.
      - Write, document and publish source code. Code is often
        less clumsy than words.  
      - Couple code and documentation. Literate analysis/programming.
      - Version control.
  o Software:
      - Documentation environment: LaTeX, fewer people also
        like Word processors, HTML for Web-based publishing
      - Computing environment:
          * language features (OOP, functions, scoping,
	    compiled code, re-usable components)
	  * high-level language (speed of getting results is not
	    only speed of running code but also of writing code)
	    and implementation principles
	  * preferably cross-platform, cross-language consistency,
	    with means for software delivery, open source
	 => R
      - Literate programming: R+Sweave, NoWeb, Mathematica Notebook,
        combining LaTeX (or other documentation) with MATLAB, Stata, Ox??
      - Version control: Subversion (client-server setup, easy-to-use
        clients available for all platforms), some still use CVS, many other
        tools for more specialized applications (Git, ...)
  o Illustrations of software tools for reproducibility:
      - Empirical analysis of a data set: data pre-processing, model
        fitting, summary (numerical and graphical).
	=> Durlauf & Johnson, Koenker?
	(maybe Luetkepohl et al./Zeileis et al.)
      - Programming a simulation and displaying the results.
        => structural change tests?
